            <p><font color = "white">This creates a problem for human survival.  Since solar panels are used to generate energy, these dust storms would significantly reduce the amount of energy and therefore light, water and oxygen and instead of producing these life-giving elements, they would be consumed – oxygen and clean water from storage tanks, while dirty water will wait to be recycled until energy is restored.  In fact, as these storms continue, lighting in greenhouses would be virtually eliminated, and many other systems would grind to a halt or, at the very least, usage would be extremely limited in an attempt to conserve power. Missions would become less frequent and extra vehicular activity (EVA) would be limited to emergencies.</font></p>
			
            <p><font color = "white">In addition, the particles of dust involved in these storms are electrostatic and so, adhere to each other and to the surfaces they cover creating a sticky mess of dust covering everything that it encounters.  Luckily, NASA has developed the capability of utilizing labyrinth seals to protect gears hydraulics and other moving parts of equipment so that these particles are less likely to “gum up the works” but it is still an issue that needs to be dealt with. Scientists and engineers have also made the equipment for Mars of the toughest metals, and glass is made of high-grade polymer, so they won’t be damaged in the dust storms.  When the two rovers that are already on Mars encountered a dust storm, they had to power down and, in essence, go into survival mode until the storm was over.</font></p>
			
				
